{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Graceful, self-healing handling of LLM failures across the three gate operations (plan-review, code-review, completion-verify), replacing today's opaque single-error collapse.\n\n## Context\n\nThe three LLM gate ops run on pydantic-ai (1.107.0, Anthropic-direct). Today every LLM failure collapses into one opaque `LLMUnavailableError` at `src/rebar/llm/runner.py:349-361`: a 429 is indistinguishable from an auth failure, there is no intentional rate-limit/backoff handling (rebar silently inherits the Anthropic SDK's default 2 retries but does nothing deliberate with them), and a whole class of \"silent-success\" failures (refusal-returned-as-content, truncated-but-looks-complete, silent hangs) is never caught.\n\nThis epic makes LLM failure handling **self-healing where possible and honest where not**, uniformly across the three gates, grounded in how the OSS community (Anthropic/OpenAI SDKs, pydantic-ai, LangGraph, Instructor, Claude Agent SDK) solves these problems. Settled design decisions (see child stories for detail + citations):\n\n- **Self-healing retry at the httpx transport layer** (`AsyncTenacityTransport`): a transient 429/529/5xx mid-agentic-run is re-sent *below* the agent graph, so already-executed (side-effecting) tools are never repeated. SDK `max_retries=0` keeps retries at one layer. 529 added explicitly; `Retry-After` honored and capped.\n- **Classify what survives retries** into a closed resolution-disposition set (WAIT_AND_RETRY, RETRY_NOW, CHANGE_SETTINGS, CHANGE_INPUT, CHANGE_PROVIDER_OR_MODEL, INCREASE_PROVIDER_LIMITS, FIX_AGENT_DESIGN, NEEDS_INVESTIGATION) paired with a verbatim `diagnostic`. The class is a best-effort routing/messaging hint; only the binary retry-or-not is behaviour-critical.\n- **Two-scope gate posture:** a *systemic* failure → block-but-retryable (all three gates uniform, distinct exit code 11, never certify); a *per-criterion/per-unit* failure → the existing drop-and-continue fail-open is **preserved**.\n- **Activity-based liveness, not total-runtime timeout:** generous per-request read timeout + step caps + an idle-watchdog that resets on each stream event (matching LangGraph `TimeoutPolicy.idle_timeout` and the Claude Agent SDK stall watchdog). No total-runtime timeout — a healthy long run is never truncated.\n- **Silent-success layer:** wall-clock timeout, verdict schema-shape check, structured refusal-as-content detection, and build-time capability/config lints — plus two additive output self-heal tweaks (schema-guided json-repair; faulty-output-in-reask) on top of rebar's already-strong `structured.py` ladder.\n- **Never certify a degraded result** (structural guard on signing). `--force` / `--force-close` / feature-off short-circuit before any of this code runs.\n\n## Architecture constraints & verified assumptions\nThese were verified against the codebase / pydantic-ai 1.107.0 during planning and constrain the design:\n- **Synchronous runner (`agent.run_sync()`, runner.py:323,461,474).** There is no event loop, so the LangGraph/Claude-SDK-style async stream-event idle-watchdog is NOT built now — liveness is achieved with `run_sync`-compatible mechanisms (per-request read timeout + per-tool timeout + step caps). The async watchdog is deferred to an ADR + follow-on ticket gated on an async-runner migration.\n- **Transport-retry dependency + injection point.** `AsyncTenacityTransport`/`tenacity` are NOT currently installed — `pydantic-ai-slim[retries]` must be added. Injection is viable: `AnthropicProvider` accepts `http_client=`/`anthropic_client=` (verified signature), so a retrying httpx client is passed with SDK `max_retries=0`. This is the riskiest integration point and is de-risked by a spike before dependent work builds on it.\n- **No streaming.** The runner uses buffered `run_sync`, so mid-stream partial-byte retry is out of scope; retries operate on whole request/response pairs.\n- **Exit-code signal.** Exit 11 vs the existing INDETERMINATE exit 2 is bifurcated by the `resolution_class` carried on the verdict `coverage`, not by a new ad-hoc flag; recorded as an ADR.\n- **Diagnostic sanitization.** The verbatim diagnostic is scrubbed of secrets/credentials/PII before any sink (logs, CLI stderr, session log, verdict); recorded as an ADR.\n- **Shared-file integration.** `runner.py`, `config.py`/`_config_schema.py`, the verdict schemas, and the docs are touched by multiple children; the gate-wiring story is the named integrator (merge order 0→1→{2,3,4,5}→6) and single-source-of-truth for the config namespace, verdict-schema edits, and the taxonomy/retry/timeout docs.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- A transient provider blip during any gate op self-heals with no operator action and no duplicated tool side effects.\n- When a failure is unrecoverable, all three gates block-but-retryable with a distinct exit code and an actionable, class-specific message, and never produce a signed/certified verdict.\n- The existing per-criterion fail-open resilience is preserved (one flaky finder among N does not block a claim).\n- A healthy multi-minute / large-context agentic run is never truncated; a genuinely stalled (\"zombie\") run is caught by the idle-watchdog + step caps.\n- Silent-success failures (refusal-as-content, empty/truncated-looks-complete, silent hang) are detected and routed, not returned as a bogus PASS/BLOCK.\n- The design is proven by a RED test suite that injects the full failure matrix through the pydantic-ai `model_override` seam.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] All 7 child stories are delivered, each passing its own acceptance criteria and CI (`make lint && make typecheck && make test`).\n- [ ] Retry is owned at exactly one layer (the httpx transport), SDK `max_retries=0`; 529 is retried; `Retry-After` is honored and capped.\n- [ ] Every LLM failure is classified into the closed resolution-disposition enum + verbatim diagnostic; the classifier is total (unknown → NEEDS_INVESTIGATION) and never itself raises.\n- [ ] All three gates share the two-scope posture: systemic → block-but-retryable (exit 11, unsigned); per-criterion fail-open preserved.\n- [ ] Agentic ops use activity-based liveness (idle-watchdog + per-request timeout + step caps); no total-runtime timeout exists in the gate path.\n- [ ] Silent-success detection + the two output self-heal tweaks are in place; a degraded/INDETERMINATE verdict can never be signed (structural guard).\n- [ ] `--force`, `--force-close`, and feature-disabled paths never enter the failure-handling code (asserted by test).\n- [ ] The transport-injection integration point is de-risked by a spike before dependent stories build on it; `pydantic-ai-slim[retries]` is added as a dependency.\n- [ ] ADRs are recorded for: the exit-11-vs-INDETERMINATE contract, the diagnostic-sanitization contract, the deferred async stream-event watchdog (+ its migration trigger), and the scope-vs-title breadth.\n- [ ] Docs cover the taxonomy, the retry/timeout model, the `run_sync`-compatible liveness design, and the config keys (single source of truth, owned by the gate-wiring story).","title":"Resilient, self-healing handling of all LLM failure modes across the three gates (rate-limits, budget, outages, timeouts, silent-success) — plan/code review + completion verify"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783559001573870001,"uuid":"de5e1ed6-282a-4788-981c-ba38c8b62a73"}